<br>
In any case, if there actually was a true Armor Lord out there, the Fundament would definitely know about it by now. The Fundament still occupied a few fortresses in the south; a good distance beyond the Fotenburg Plain and far to the north of the Hungry River. The Fundament held its forces at rest on the edge of the Blasphemous Lands, just beyond the two cities that bordered the Grand Seal. Caltrin and Nalfador were the names of the two cities, places where cutthroats and cutpurses were respectable professions. The two cities had allied themselves with Oztrenoth during the War of Redemption, and had served as blockades to slow the advance of the Fundament when they made their march into the south. The two cities had a great advantage defensively, since they were positioned high atop plateaus that overlooked the entirety of the surrounding lands. During the War of Redemption, they had lined up rows upon rows of ballistic engines of war on the edge of the plateaus, and had used them to shower their advancing enemies with fiery death and swarms of arrows. <br>
<br>
The land encircling the two cities was oftentimes enough to impede the progress of even the hardiest armies. Craters dotted the roughly hewn landscape, making roadways impassable or greatly reducing the speed at which an army could traverse them. Stacks of crags filed across the land in slanting rows, as if a giant farmer had uplifted them all with a single stroke from a massive hoe. Though not quite in the Realm of Malediction, this land still held many of its characteristics. Airborne clouds of dust criss-crossed the suns like a veil, netting out half the light being passed down from them.  The loose ashy soil was an ailment, coughing up more arid tendrils of dirt with each thrust of the wind. Only a few parceled shreds of green shrubbery found themselves a refuge within the cracks and nooks of boulders and dry land, making the place an altogether colorless region, aside from the predominant brown. Suitable farmland was hard pressed to find here; a few large, sectioned off areas of land were fed water and fertilizer daily, to create soil where crops wouldn’t whither away mid season. Before the War of Redemption, the two cities had mostly relied on outside trade to satisfy their supply needs, but now they were severely cut off from the rest of the world, and had mainly themselves to depend upon. Caltrin and Nalfador had been known for producing some of the finest in weaponry and armor, but now they manufactured little of either, since their main struggle had been shifted to survival. <br>
<br>
After the War of Redemption, the Fundament had decided not to wipe out the two cities, since such a campaign would be costly to themselves. They found that the two cities would better serve them if they were left intact, producing armaments for the Fundament’s military at near production cost. In return for this, the Fundament allowed a small amount of trade to be circulated between the two cities and other kingdoms. But to insure that the two cities remained crippled––should they decide to try and rise up again––the Fundament placed heavy sanctions on any imported goods. Also a tax was placed on any exported goods, collecting no less than a third and no more than a half of total profits. It maintained poverty at a safe level, but not too low, otherwise a massive amount of people would die off. There was a govenant reigning in each city, but they were rulers who cared little for their people, and strived to please the Fundament’s every whim. That’s why uneasy tensions were growing in the south, because if the Armor Lord truly had returned, then he would likely lead the people to battle against the Fundament, overthrowing the govenants in the process. The govenants would hate to see the return of the Armor Lord just as much as the Fundament would.<br>
<br>
*****<br>
<br>
To the northeast of Kingdom Algaroy, beneath bitter skies wrapped in fluffy white curls of snow, was the kingdom known as Glamisoreat North. It was a kingdom now ruled by a single High Decka, who was very young for her position. Hallgron was the capital city; a place where every roof bulged beneath the weight of winter’s fallout. The square buildings stooped low to the ground, where the snow would pack itself almost entirely around them; it served as a second layer of insulation, with asbestos between the walls being the first. The houses were mostly single-floored complexes, with fireplaces burning gently and emitting heat from the center of the room. Windows illuminated by candles spilled out golden puddles across the snow. Black smoke rising up against the falling snow poured forth from chimney pipes on every block and street corner.  <br>
<br>
The pebble streets outside were entrenched beneath deep layers of snow, where only a path made here and there by a plowman cut through the freshly fallen flakes. The midmorning sky was a quiet gray, with more crystals of snow slowly racing their way down from the heavens, landing with tiny thuds muted to human ears. Aside from a plowman or two puffing out silver clouds of fog while they worked, the streets were deserted.<br>
<br>
The serenity of the morning drift was broken by four men carrying a large chest between them. They methodically strode down a cleared path in the street, one of them positioned at each corner of the heavy box they were lugging. Their faces were concealed behind icicle-engraved scarves and hoods, with only their reddened noses poking out into the cold air. They wore long, dark heavy coats, which looked ruffled and worn from extensive travel. The falling snow clung to wrinkles in their garments, temporarily turning their wearers into walking snowmen before melting. Their chests heaved and wheezed with each step, generating synchronized breaths of frosty mist. They didn’t speak a word to each other, but kept trudging on, fur-trimmed boots crunching through the snow. Castle Hallgron loomed over the houses in the distance; the four men and their package steadily drew closer to it.<br>
<br>
*****<br>
<br>
Heckens leaned up in his bed, then nodded toward the servant. “Thanks for the hot chocolate, leave it on my desk over there.” The suavely groomed servant bowed in acknowledgment, then proceeded to do as told. After completing his menial task, he clasped his gloved hands together and patiently awaited any further instruction. Heckens tossed off his thick blankets and stood up. “That will be all. You can go now.” The servant bowed away then exited through the door. Servants were not allowed to speak or act, unless directly addressed and told to do so.<br>
<br>
After throwing off his sleeping garments, Heckens sluggishly walked over to his wardrobe and picked out one of his advisor robes. It was a loose-fitting, royal blue robe, with nothing particularly fancy about it. The white snow owl, the sign of House Stellra, was stitched into the left and right breast. The two detailed owls stood tall on an olive branch with their backs facing one another, maintaining a guarded expression within their sunken eyes. The robe had a high neck collar, which went all the way up and barely touched Heckens’ chin. The collar was gilded with silver and inscribed with blocky symbols that held little meaning.<br>
<br>
After slipping into his attire and finding it to be a comfortable fit, Heckens walked over to his washstand and mirror. He bent over and looked into the gold-framed mirror; the reflection of his own dark eyes stared back at him. His long midnight beard was a tangled and matted clump, with a few rebellious hairs twisting off like broken lute strings. “Not again... at times it would seem maintaining this bush of hair is more trouble than it’s worth,” he grumbled to himself. He dipped his cupped hands into the crystalline waters of the washbasin, then splashed a few quarts of it onto his face. Having a beard was almost necessary to keep one’s skin from freezing over in this land, so he couldn’t easily part with it. After his beard was thoroughly soaked, he clamped both hands around it and rang it out like a wet sponge, spraying drops out onto the velvet carpet and tubby washbasin.  <br>
<br>
Heckens made a few more minor adjustments to his hair and robes, then walked over to his desk to pick up the mug of hot chocolate. While reaching down to grab the steaming cup, he took a quick glance out the window behind his desk. The window panes held up slopes of thick frost, so it was difficult to discern what lay beyond, but Heckens was still able to make out the shapes of several figures marching up the pathway in the courtyard below. There were four outsiders, holding some kind of box between them. They were escorted by several castle guards, men who were dressed in heavy black pelts beneath the cold steel of their breastplates. The guards wore large thick mittens, which resembled black pompons. Heckens could not even distinguish their fingers, it looked like their hands were nothing more than black balls of fur. The guards wore tall fuzzy hats, made from the same animal hide as their gloves. Their lips were all hooked downward, boring stern expressions on their faces. Their overall appearance, and the way they marched in rhythm, reminded Heckens of a wind-up toy soldier he had played with as a boy.<br>
<br>
“Well, well. It appears the High Decka has some visitors today,” he absently muttered to himself. Lifting the mug of hot chocolate to his lips, he took a long swig. The liquid was scalding hot, he nearly burned his tongue off in the process of swallowing. Most men chose to start the day with a glass of apple cider to warm their insides, but not Heckens, he was content with a simple chocolate mixture. He would have breakfast later on, after checking on the High Decka’s condition. Depleting his drink to the last drop, he set the cup back down onto the desk with a thud. It would probably be just another day of pointless politics.<br>
<br>
A slight rapping on the door brought Heckens’ attention around. “Be there in one moment,” he vacantly told whoever was behind the door. He crossed the red velvet carpet once again, then opened the door with a twist of the golden handle, revealing Tactician Skarn on the other side. <br>
<br>
The scrupulous looking man greeted him by mildly inclining his head and plainly saying, “The dawn welcomes you.” He motioned Heckens to come out into the hall. “Come, let us go find what our High Decka’s bidding is for this day.” The square-shouldered man turned on his heel and started off down the hall, the edge of his dark cloak brushing across the floor behind him. His plated boots jangled like sleigh bells with each step, resounding off down the square corridor. Long knots of braided straw-spun hair, which argued with the color of the rest of his dark grab, bounced on his back with each step.<br>
<br>
Heckens strode out into the hallway, swiftly closing and locking the door behind him. He had to take double steps to catch up to Skarn, who was already halfway down the hall to the next door. “The dawn welcomes you as well,” he formally greeted the other. “Any news today? Anything happening that I should know about?” He asked in a blithe manner. <br>
<br>
Like always, Skarn gave him the usual runabout of things. He spoke in a voice gruffer than a goat’s, “Well, you know how things are. If we aren’t besought by smaller nations for support, then we’re likely having potential treaties being rammed down our throats by our foes. Never give in to them; is what I always say. They only want us to lower our guard, then they will try and take Cloudsunder for themselves.” The man stroked the greased tips of his three-pronged beard, seemingly trying to think of anything else. “I can’t think of anything more to tell you. Nothing that you don’t already know, anyway.”<br>
<br>
Recently a multitude of events had occurred on Falax’mertenya. There were rumors of a new leader toppling one of the Fundament’s puppet regimes in the west; though it was unlikely this would provide any advantageous opportunities for Glamisoreat North. Kingdoms challenged the Fundament all the time, and they were put down like rabid dogs as a result. There was nothing to be gained from direct opposition to them. Heckens knew that one day the Fundament would implode in on itself, so why waste a war effort on them? The Fundament was filled with hypocrites and dictators, everything that it was supposedly against. A phrase they had adopted worked equally as well on themselves, ‘Leave evil to its own unmaking.’<br>
<br>
“I hear our sworn enemies, Glamisoreat South, are receiving support from the Fundament. This could spell disaster for us,” said Heckens dismally as he turned toward his companion. “Strangely, they are reportedly heading south. I don’t know if they are making a joint war effort or if the Fundament is using Glamisoreat South just as a staging ground. It would be best to keep an eye on them, though I doubt they would launch any massive offensives on us this time of year. They would freeze to death before they made it halfway here.”<br>
<br>
Skarn’s chest rose upward then released a deep sigh. He replied in a croaky voice, “I wouldn’t worry about them. There is supposedly an Armor Lord in the south, and I’m sure they want to destroy him completely and utterly before he manages to muster up an army. I have even heard rumors of Unconsecrated Ones roaming the land again, but even if they prove true, it’s not a problem of ours. Besides, to the Fundament we are the shadow always looming just out of sight. They know we’re not a threat, unless something else drastic should happen.” The man turned and studied the tapestries passing by on the cream-colored walls. The tapestries were whiter than the eye of winter, with the darker white forms of snow owls stitched into their center. The owls were hunched low, as if prepared to swoop down from their olive branches to collect a mouse. Their faces were etched with boundless wisdom––as much wisdom as could be presented by a masterful sewing hand, anyway.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
After passing through several doors and several more halls, the double doors leading to the Chamber of Ancestors appeared just ahead. A few servants going about their business stopped and bowed out of the way as Skarn and Heckens came through. Heckens had lived here nearly all his life, but the Chamber of Ancestors was still an eerie place to him. Skarn and he each pushed a door open, then entered into the darkened, domed room of the Chamber of Ancestors. The majority of light was closed off in the hall left behind, now, the only source of illumination stemmed from a few freshly lit torch stands. Long shadows played games of hide and seek across the walls, to the bidding of torch flames which bended and swayed in a fiery limbo. The walls were not entirely walls though. Glass showcases, as tall as an average-sized man, lined the dimly lit walls all around the circular chamber. A person was inside each one of them, or what had been a person at one point. The people inside looked as real as they had on the day they left the mortal coil. It was almost as if they were frozen in cubes of ice, never to walk or speak again, but always watching over the chamber with inexhaustible eyes. They were all ancestors of the High Decka, some dating back hundreds of years ago. Advisors and other important council members were preserved here as well; Heckens knew that one day he would join them. This room was a reminder that nothing lasts forever: cities, men, and beliefs were all meaningless in the end. <br>
<br>
The figures behind the glass stood silently with palms raised outward, as if offering the living a chance to come and take their place. The embalmers and taxidermists did an excellent job of capturing their life and immortalizing it in this way. Many historical faces, glowing a dull orange from torchlight reflections, stared out with astuteness that could never be lost. Heckens could almost see their lips move and hear their voices. Valaren, the Grand Duke, imperialistically stood over in one corner. A sword clasped firmly in his fist was held out before him in a permanent salute. In his mind, Heckens could hear, “My sword, my life, my honor.”  <br>
<br>
Skarn stifled out a hearty chuckle. “What’s the matter with you? I thought this place frightened you, yet you seem completely absorbed in it. Should I tell the High Decka you’re not coming today?” He grabbed Heckens by his shoulder and roughly pushed him forward. “Let’s go already.”<br>
<br>
Heckens nodded and compliantly continued walking along. “Sorry, it just seems the dead have much to say, if one only stops and listens.” They strode down the steps of the chamber and arrived at the door on the other side. The High Decka’s bedroom was down another two or three hallways. It really was a long walk every morning; he sometimes wished the castle’s architects hadn’t been so spacious.<br>
<br>
“I envy dead men. They have no regrets,” docilely grumbled Skarn to himself. The two of them finally arrived at the High Decka’s bedroom. Skarn gently knocked on the door, then crossed his arms and waited impatiently. “I wonder if the High Decka’s condition has been escalated or relieved some?” <br>
<br>
“There’s no telling for sure. We can just count ourselves lucky that the Achromatic Plague hasn’t stricken here in full force yet. I wonder what could cause such an...an epidemic? The High Decka hasn’t shown any plague symptoms yet, it would seem her illness is something else,” replied Heckens in a sympathetic tone. The High Decka’s health was fading rapidly––even though she was only fourteen years old! She was the last in a long lineage known as House Stellra.<br>
<br>
The door opened a crack and the well-rounded face of a middle-aged lady appeared. Beneath her thin eyelashes, two sapphire eyes surveyed the pair of men standing before her. She waved her arm and motioned them to enter. She spoke in an uncouth manner, “Come in. The High Decka has been expecting you like always.”<br>
<br>
Their shoulders swung with each step as they marched into the room, trying to look stern and disciplined in front of their High Decka. Their efforts were fruitlessly spent though. The High Decka lay face down atop a mountain of blankets and pillows, her arms sprawled flat out to her sides. Steam rose from a cup full of fresh soup resting atop her bedside dresser; it looked like her serving maiden hadn’t been able to spoon any of it into her mouth. <br>
<br>
The room was on ground level, with banks of snow just outside nearly reaching up to the windowsill. A small fireplace opposite the window blazed and sparked with fresh kindling, popping and spitting up ash every now and then. The tiled floor was glossy and spotless, whoever cleaned this room had it down to a science. A few chairs carved from hickory sat vacant against the walls, their rims facing the bed.<br>
<br>
There were two others in the room besides the serving maiden and themselves. John Brahn the Crooked turned his doughy face toward them as they entered, his misaligned eyes squinting behind rectangular spectacles. He was by all means a dwarf man, and he prided himself on it. John was a product of incestial relationships between dwarves before him, because long ago dwarves had been commodities among high ruling people; they served as entertainers and comedians. Awhile back, a large family of dwarves had been adopted by the Stellra family. These dwarves were all talented circus performers and accomplished comedians who thrived on their roles in entertainment, but to insure that their kind would live on, they had to inbreed, since other outsider dwarves were difficult to come across. Each generation spawning from their tight gene pool only became more twisted and crazed. Just looking at John was enough to make anyone sprout lumps, and be thankful that the union of their parents was not a sacrilegious one. The dwarf’s chin had more slopes and curves than a hilly landscape; indeed, much more than any humanoid creature deserved. He had more facial hair than most animals, and it was singed in many places, where he had decided it would be a good idea to light it on fire, because if there was one hobby John was good at it was starting things on fire. The dwarf was a pyro menace, and should be banished from the castle forever, but he made the High Decka laugh, and that was enough to earn his keep. Heckens was grateful that John was the last little scamp left, since most of the others had died at birth, or were born short a heart or other vital organ.<br>
<br>
Seated across from the fireplace was the hulk of a man known as Gunro, the Tumlander. He was a giant brute garbed in onyx leather, with his bare muscular arms bulging almost to the point of bursting. Blood vessels as thick as rope twined their way up and down his arms, disappearing beneath plated shoulder pads and heavy jet-black gauntlets. He came from Tumland, and was the High Decka’s personal guardian. He never spoke a word, reserving himself to a quiet vigilance over things he had no control over. Dark emotionless eyes, hidden behind long strands of loose black hair, flared up orange with each roar from the fireplace. His face was a livid mask which spoke louder than words, and people nearby were wise enough to listen, knowing that this man was not one who liked to be bothered. In his younger years he had been a guardian to the previous High Decka, but disease had claimed her life, and now the same thing was happening to the current High Decka. There was nothing a great warrior like himself could do about it either, his massive sword could not slay a virus.  Watching and hoping was all that could be done at a time like this.<br>
<br>
“How are you doing today, High Decka Dalfoy?” asked Heckens, unable to hide the touch of worriment in his voice. The young girl was still dressed in her silken sleeping garments, laying unmoving on her stomach. She struggled with the monumental task of twisting herself onto her back, then looked out at her two advisors through famished eyes. Great bags of purple sagged low beneath those cool eyes, either from lack of sleep or lack of nourishment, probably both. Millage, the woman who had opened the door for them, rushed to her side in case she should fall.<br>
<br>
“Do I look like I’m doing well? I am too weak to even step out of bed and take a bath! Why has this happened to me?” Her high-strung voice was powerless, despite the demanding force she tried to put behind it. She brushed a matted black curl of hair out of her face. “I can’t eat and I can’t sleep. When will those damned Hamotsfu Priests arrive and cure me!?” She fell back on her pillows, out of breath from shouting. The color of her skin was a yellow deeper than a bale of golden wheat. All her bones protruded throughout her entire frame; she looked like nothing more than a skeleton bundled up in a yellow bag. She was so thin, so frail. One touch and she might shatter into a million pieces.<br>
<br>
“I saw a group of strange looking men heading up to the castle earlier, perhaps they are the priests? They were heavily garbed, so it was difficult to see who they were,” replied Heckens. He could tell the High Decka wasn’t really listening though, her chest inflated and deflated like a bagpipe, and it always seemed like her next intake of air would be her last, but somehow she fought on. <br>
<br>
